[[Image:Conways game of life breeder animation.gif|thumb|379px|Evolution of an MSM breeder – a [[puffer train|puffer]] that produces [[Gosper gun]]s, which in turn emit [[glider (Conway's Life)|glider]]s.]] <!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Chart animation.gif|thumb|379px|Charts showing the change of cell count per generation of the four different breeder types. A polynomial trend line demonstrates the quadratic growth rate. {{ifdc|Chart animation.gif|log=2014 March 22}}]] -->
In [[cellular automaton|cellular automata]] such as [[Conway's Game of Life]], a '''breeder''' is a pattern that exhibits [[quadratic growth]], by generating multiple copies of a secondary pattern, each of which then generates multiple copies of a tertiary pattern.<ref name="weisstein">{{cite web |url=http://www.ericweisstein.com/encyclopedias/life/Breeder.html |accessdate=2008-11-01| title = Breeder – from Eric Weisstein's Treasure Trove of Life C.A.}}</ref>
==Classification== Breeders can be classed by the relative motion of the patterns. The classes are denoted by three-letter codes, which denote whether the primary, secondary and tertiary elements respectively are moving (M) or stationary (S). The four basic types are:<ref name="weisstein" /> * SMM – A [[Gun (cellular automaton)|gun]] that fires out [[Rake (cellular automaton)|rakes]]. * MSM – A [[Puffer train|puffer]] that leaves [[Gun (cellular automaton)|guns]] in its wake. * MMS – A [[Rake (cellular automaton)|rake]] that fires out [[Puffer train (cellular automaton)|puffers]]. * MMM – A [[Rake (cellular automaton)|rake]] that fires out more [[Rake (cellular automaton)|rakes]], such that there are no stationary elements.
A [[spacefiller]] (which also undergoes quadratic growth) may be thought of as a fifth class of breeder. However it differs from a true breeder in that it expands a single island of cells, rather than creating independent objects.
