A '''calendrical calculation''' is a [[calculation]] concerning [[calendar date]]s. Calendrical calculations can be considered an area of [[applied mathematics]]. Calendrical calculation is one of the five major [[Savant syndrome]] characteristics. Some examples of calendrical calculations:
* Converting a [[Julian calendar|Julian]] or [[Gregorian calendar]] date to its [[Julian day]] number and vice versa (see [[Julian day#Calculation|the section on calculation in that article]] for details). * The number of days between two dates, which is simply the difference in their Julian day numbers. * The date of a religious holiday, like [[Easter]] (the calculation is known as [[Computus]]) or [[Passover]], for a given year. * Converting a date between different calendars. For instance, dates in the [[Gregorian calendar]] can be converted to dates in the [[Islamic calendar]] with the [[Kuwaiti algorithm]]. * [[Calculating the day of the week]].
==References== * [[Edward M. Reingold]] and [[Nachum Dershowitz]]. ''Calendrical Calculations''. [[Cambridge University Press]]; 3 edition (December 10, 2007). {{ISBN|978-0-521-88540-9}}
