{{Infobox scientist | name = Karl Wilhelm Feuerbach | image = Karl Wilhelm Feuerbach.jpg | caption = Karl Wilhelm Feuerbach | birth_date = 30 May 1800 | birth_place = [[Jena]], [[Saxe-Weimar]], [[Holy Roman Empire]] | death_date = 12 March 1834 | death_place =[[Erlangen]], [[German Confederation|Germany]] | nationality = German | field = [[Mathematician]] | work_institution = [[University of Basel]] | alma_mater = [[University of Freiburg|Albert Ludwigs University of Freiburg]] | known_for = [[Feuerbach's theorem]] | religion = [[Lutheran]] | footnotes= Brother of [[Ludwig Feuerbach|Ludwig Andreas Feuerbach]]}} '''Karl Wilhelm von Feuerbach''' (30 May 1800 &ndash; 12 March 1834) was a German [[geometer]] and the son of legal scholar [[Paul Johann Anselm Ritter von Feuerbach]], and the brother of philosopher [[Ludwig Feuerbach]]. After receiving his doctorate at age 22, he became a professor of [[mathematics]] at the [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] at [[Erlangen]]. In 1822 he wrote a small book on mathematics noted mainly for a theorem on the [[nine-point circle]], which is now known as [[Feuerbach's theorem]]. In 1827 he introduced [[homogeneous coordinates]], independently of [[August Ferdinand Möbius|Möbius]].<ref>[http://sfabel.tripod.com/mathematik/database/Feuerbach.html M20 Mathematik LK Facharbeit: Karl Wilhelm Feuerbach]</ref>
