In [[mathematical analysis]], the '''Rademacher–Menchov theorem''', introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Rademacher|authorlink=Hans Rademacher|year=1922}} and {{harvs|txt|authorlink=Dmitrii Menshov|last=Menchoff|year=1923}}, gives a [[sufficient condition]] for a series of [[orthogonal functions]] on an interval to converge [[almost everywhere]].

==Statement==

If the coefficients ''c''<sub>ν</sub> of a series of bounded orthogonal functions on an interval satisfy
:<math>\sum |c_\nu|^2\log(\nu)^2<\infty</math>
then the series converges almost everywhere.

